The amplitude of wave 3 can be computed via Fourier decomposition of the mean seasonal field (AM method) or by computing the mean amplitude of the instantaneous monthly fields (MA method). The ratio MA/AM can be used as a meassure of the stationarity of the zonal wave 3 since a perfectly stationary wave (withouth change in phase) would have a ratio equal to 1 and a completely unstationary wave (with completely random phase) would have a ratio close to zero

The amplitude of QS3 achieves its maximum at near 200hPa and 50S in all seasons but with important changes in its vertical extent. During austral winter and autum, wave 3 amplitude extends up to the higest model levels while it remains restricted to the stratosphere during spring and summer. In general, the high amplitudes are colocated with areas of high stationarity, although this metric is maximized at lower levels with the exception of spring. While the mean wave amplitude during this season is high (not shown), stationarity is low in the midlatitudes and specially in the high stratosphere. This is due primarily by the behaviour during november, when high phase variance means that wave 3 cannot be considered stationary.

Wave 3 component of the geopotential field of each season at 200hPa.

The reconstructed QS3 field at 200hPa show the expected maximum at 50S and the anual cycle in its phase already observed in previous studies. It also shows an easterly inclination of the systems evident in summer but absent in winter, suggesting that the QS3 might be related to southerly transport of momentum.

Mean wave 3 component of geopotential height between 65S and 35S

The vertical strucure of the QS3 shows that the expected seasonal cycle in vertical extent is followed by a slight inclination of the disturances.

Taken together, this suggests a mix of baroclinic and barotropic processes related to the QS3. The former, more important during summer and the the latter dominating in winter. (Esto se debera ver con la energtica)

Seasonal cicle of QS3 index.

ZW3 activiy exhibits a clear annual cycle with higher amplitude during the austral winter months and lower amplitude during the summer months. This annual cycle is consistent with previous work [@Loon1972; @Karoly1985; @Raphael2004].

As suggested previously, the low amplitude of QS3 wave in spring is not due to a reduction in the amplitude of the planetary wave 3 but to its reduced stationarity.

Regression of 200hPa geopotential height and QS3 standarized index, and wave acivity flux computed from regression of 0.201 sigma.

All months show evidence of planetary wave 3 activity, but with considerable heterogeneity in its characteristics. In January, September and December, zonal wave 3 is related to a wave train emanating from the tropical western Pacific propagating to the southeast and then turning to the northeast.

En enero, se observa un patrn hemisfrico de onda 3, con un centro anmalamente negativo importante en el Pacfico sudeste, embebido adems en un tren de ondas extendido entre el este de Nueva Zelanda, y Sudamrica. En febrero, la estructura se mantiene similar, pero con menor evidencia de propagacin meridional, y el centro anticiclnico en Sudamrica intensificado y un debilitamiento de aquel ubicado al sur del ndico. En marzo, la estructura de onda 3 exhibe mnima variacin meridional y ocupa todo el crculo de latitud entre 60S y 45S. Abril es similar a marzo, pero sin centros ciclnicos significativos. En mayo, se distingue nuevamente un tren de ondas con propagacin meridional, emanando desde Australia, pero con evidencias de reflexin en el Mar de Weddell. Junio, al igual que marzo, presenta una estructura de QS3 zonal, pero menos definida y, consistente con el corrimiento de la fase observado, con los centros ciclnicos y anticiclnicos desplazados hacia el oeste.
